{"author":{"id":"cff9ab1d2ee9741039b2a60d90cca378a5320ba753398f6f3df8d03abcebee1b"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1771596754,"nonce":"DlvW64Yo9VfsV5xCBRsbtf5z8EY=","metadata":{"github-id":"IC_kwDORKr0287qjHS8","github-url":"https://github.com/bonanzahq/bonanza/issues/136#issuecomment-3935073468"},"message":"Proposed approach: magic link authentication via email.\n\nBorrowers already have email addresses on file and the system has an existing email token pattern (used for email confirmation). The same mechanism works here:\n\n1. Staff clicks 'Send deletion link' on the borrower's page\n2. System emails the borrower a tokenized magic link\n3. Borrower clicks the link, sees what will happen (anonymize vs full delete), and confirms\n4. Action is recorded in the GDPR audit log with the borrower as the initiator\n\nThis reuses existing infrastructure (email tokens, mailer setup) and keeps the borrower-facing surface minimal (one confirmation page). Staff retains control over when the process starts, and the borrower's click-through creates a clear consent trail.\n\nA fully self-initiated flow (borrower triggers deletion without staff involvement) would require a borrower login system which doesn't exist. The magic link approach avoids that entirely.","files":null}]}